rows.text: A potato soup with regional variations
Made from melted cheese blended into mashed potatoes (often with some garlic)
A dish of cauliflower, potato and turmeric. It is sometimes prepared with additional spices.
A dish of potatoes, bechamel sauce and meat. the bechamel made by flour butter milk and white pepper powder.
Potatoes with meat, usually lamb or mutton, in a stew-like gravy
A soft, calzone-shaped pie filled with boiled, spiced and mashed potatoes and other vegetables like green peas or chana dal, and fried
Poppy seed paste and potato pieces cooked together with mustard oil and dry black chillis
A mix of sliced potatoes, sliced onions, cubed mutton, beef and pork which have been marinated overnight in Alsatian white wine and juniper berries and slow cooked in a sealed ceramic casserole dish.
A potato baked in an oven, typically, but not always, served whole
Mashed potatoes with sausages, topped with gravy
A spicy dish made of potatoes, red peppers, coriander, chili, and garlic which are all fried together in olive oil
A type of savory fritter. This snack food can also be made with lentil, dal, or gram flour.
A breakfast dish made from fried potatoes, eggs, onions, leeks or chives, and bacon or ham. It is similar to the somewhat simpler English bubble and squeak.
Potatoes that are baked with spices, peppers and curry, and then battered and deep fried
A typical South Indian snack prepared with potatoes or other vegetables. There are various sweet and spicy versions in different regions.

A dish of mashed potatoes, butter, and whole milk or cream. An indent in the mashed potatoes is made to form a well into which bacon cubes that have been fried along with some sliced onions are placed.
Potato dumplings with sheep cheese and bacon
File:Full English breakfast with bubble and squeak, sausage, bacon, grilled tomatoes, and eggs.jpg
A traditional dish made with leftovers, the main ingredients being potato and cabbage.
Potatoes, onions, and often meat (bacon or sausage) cooked in a Dutch oven
A traditional baked potato dish eaten in the Canary Islands that is usually served with a pepper sauce called Mojo, or as an accompaniment to meat dishes.
Typically consists of french fries, carne asada, guacamole, sour cream and cheese. The dish is high in calories, with a meal-sized portion containing 2000 calories (kcal) or more.
A national dish that's also very popular in the northeastern part of Poland, it's a type of dumpling made from riced potatoes and usually stuffed with minced meat
A dumpling prepared with boiled potatoes and wheat flour.
A popular fast food dish consisting of french fries covered in cheese
For the fried potato sticks, see {{section link||French fries}}. For the crisp, sliced potatoes, see {{section link||Potato chip}}.
For the fried potato sticks, see {{section link||French fries}}. For the crisp, sliced potatoes, see {{section link||Potato chip}}.
For the fried potato sticks, see {{section link||French fries}}. For the crisp, sliced potatoes, see {{section link||Potato chip}}.
File:Crab dip and old bay chips.jpg
A food combination consisting of various types of chips or crisps and various dips. Pictured is crab dip with potato chips.
File:Shortbread cookies and chocolate-covered potato chips.jpg
Potato chips that have been dipped into melted chocolate or cocoa, and coated with the chocolate.
French fries topped with sliced beef and sausages, scrambled eggs and fried onions

A freeze-dried potato product traditionally made by Quechua and Aymara communities of Bolivia and Peru, and is known in various countries of South America, including Argentina, Bolivia, Chile and Peru.

A traditional Scottish dish that originated in Orkney, it's created by the combined mashing of swede turnips and potatoes ("neeps and tatties") with the addition of chives, butter or dripping, salt and pepper. Some versions include onions.

Often made to use up leftovers, and therefore without a specific recipe, coddle most commonly consists of layers of roughly sliced pork sausages and rashers (thinly sliced, somewhat fatty back bacon) with sliced potatoes and onions.
A traditional Irish dish mainly consisting of mashed potatoes with kale or cabbage.
Made from corned beef, onion and often thinly sliced, cubed or mashed potato. Corned beef pie is pictured at the left in the image.
This dish consists of a bottom layer of minced beef, with a top layer of mashed potatoes. A variation using lamb mince is known as shepherd's pie.
A sandwich that includes crisps (potato chips) as one of the fillings. In addition to the crisps, any other common sandwich ingredient may be added.
Made from mashed potato and egg, which is covered in bread crumbs and fried
A small bread-crumbed fried food roll that may be prepared with many various ingredients such as potato, ground meats, cheese and vegetables, among others.

A snack food of India, originating in the Kutch or Kachchh region of Gujarat. It is a spicy snack made by mixing boiled potatoes with a dabeli masala, and putting the mixture between pav (burger bun) and served with chutneys made from tamarind, date, garlic, red chilies, etc.
Consist of a purée of mashed potato and egg yolk, butter, salt, pepper, nutmeg, which is forced from a piping bag or hand-moulded into various shapes which are then baked
Potatoes, usually smaller ones, are first deep fried, then cooked slowly at low flame in a gravy with spices.
Snack food composed primarily of potato starch and tinted sago. They may also contain tapioca and wheat flour.
A traditional casserole with a layer of white fish in béchamel sauce underneath, and a layer of mashed potatoes on top.
A common potato dish that consists of French fries (fresh cut or frozen) topped with gravy, ground beef, and green peas.
One or two potato fritters enclosed in a floury bap (bread roll) and is usually served with salt and vinegar, sometimes with tomato ketchup or brown sauce atop the fritters.
Intermountain West region of the United States

A traditional potato hotdish, or casserole of the Intermountain West region. People called this dish funeral potatoes because the casserole is commonly served as a side dish during traditional after-funeral dinners,
Dumplings made from ground potato and chopped vegetables in a clear broth
A variety of jeon, or Korean style pancake, made by pan-frying finely grated potato on a frying pan with vegetable oil

A spicy Korean soup made with pork spine or ribs, vegetables and other ingredients. It is a matter of contention whether the name of the soup comes from the word for potato (감자; gamja) or not, because the soup is frequently served without potatoes.
A preparation of fries in which potatoes are sliced into uniform sizes and shapes, fried or deep fried and sometimes prepared with additional cooked ingredients such as onion, green pepper and bacon
File:Gnocchi di ricotta burro e salvia.jpg
Thick, soft dumplings that may be made from semolina, ordinary wheat flour, flour and egg, flour, egg, and cheese, potato, breadcrumbs, or similar ingredients.

A widespread culinary technique in food preparation in which an ingredient is topped with a browned crust, often using breadcrumbs, grated cheese, egg and/or butter. Gratin is usually prepared in a shallow dish of some kind. It is baked or cooked under an overhead grill or broiler to form a golden crust on top and is traditionally served in its baking dish.
Made with mashed, baked potato, combined with diced meat and sauce lyonnaise and served in the potato shells.
Deep fried potato chips topped with doner kebab meat and cheese. The dish is topped with a trio of garlic sauce, chilli sauce and BBQ sauce
Potato pieces that are pan-fried after being shredded, julienned, diced, or riced.
A baked potato cut about halfway through into thin slices and topped with butter and other ingredients.

A type of basic potato dish made by pan- or skillet-frying chunked, sliced, wedged or diced potatoes that are sometimes unpeeled and may have been par-cooked by boiling, baking, steaming, or microwaving.
Bread (usually white) with a hamburger patty placed on top that is then covered in French fries and topped with brown (beef) gravy
Boiled and mashed potatoes, carrots and onion
A traditional casserole made of potatoes, onions, pickled sprats, bread crumbs and cream. It is commonly included in a Swedish Christmas smörgåsbord.
Fries, topped with döner or shawarma meat, grilled with a layer of Gouda cheese until melted and then subsequently covered with a layer of dressed salad greens
A savory snack consisting of potato, usually covered in dough, baked, grilled, or deep fried.
Large round poached or boiled potato or bread dumplings, made without yeast
Breton for 'potato cake', it's prepared with crushed boiled potatoes mixed with flour. The resulting dough is then shaped into small pancakes and then pan fried.
Potato dumplings with a filling of onions and pork or bacon.
A pudding or casserole made from egg noodles or potatoes.
Potatoes, bacon, milk, onions, and eggs, baked in a low casserole dish
A soup based on sourdough and mushrooms
In Ashkenazi cuisine, a potato pancake made with grated potato
A traditional flatbread prepared with leftover potatoes and flour
Fried potato patties or thick pancakes stuffed with cheese
Sliced pan-fried potatoes and thinly sliced onions, sautéed in butter with parsley
A dish of potatoes that have been boiled and mashed, typically prepared with milk and butter.
A Thai curry of meat, most often prepared with halal meats such as beef or chicken due to its Persian origin, and potatoes.
File:Grandma Pollards meat and potato pies (5815022642).jpg
A meat and potato pie has a similar filling to a Cornish Pasty and differs from a meat pie in that its content is often minced and usually less than 50% meat. They are typically eaten as take-aways.
A savory pancake made with potato flour.
A stew of potatoes and onion with sweetened soy sauce

A salad with many variations. Also known as Russian salad or Stolichny salad. It usually includes potatoes, diced boiled chicken (or sometimes ham or bologna sausage), eggs, brined dill pickles, carrots, green peas and onions, dressed with mayonnaise. Variations of this salad are also popular in Eastern Europe, the Balkans, Spain, as well as in some Asian and South American countries.
A casserole dish consisting of meat (mainly corned beef) and root vegetables (mainly potatoes and onions) left to bake throughout the day in an oven pot on low heat
An appetizer of boiled yellow potatoes (similar to the Yukon Gold potatoes) in a spicy, creamy sauce called Huancaína sauce
Mashed potatoes stuffed with seasoned ground meat and spices that is deep fried
A red potato and creamy cheese dish served with onion and tomato
A baked pastry, a traditional variety of which is particularly associated with Cornwall, the westernmost county in England. It is made by placing uncooked filling typically of meat and vegetables

Often served as a tapa in bars. It typically consists of white potatoes that have been cut into irregular shapes of about 2 centimeters, fried in oil and served warm with a sauce such as a spicy tomato sauce or an aioli
Slow cooked grated potatoes, onions, salt and spearmint
A speciality of the Limousin and the Allier (Bourbonnais) regions in Central France, its main ingredients are potato slices and crème fraîche, which are used to fill a puff pastry crust
A battered and deep fried disc of mashed potato, seasoned with sage and onion. It is sold in the port towns of Hartlepool, Kingston upon Hull and Liverpool.
Prepared with fried potatoes and Reblochon cheese
A flat, fried or baked potato dish that can be considered a kind of flattened dumpling or pancake
Mostly made of raw potatoes and barley flour; the dish has many varieties
Sliced, layered potatoes cooked in lots of melted butter
File:Saddle of Rabbit, Confit San Manzano Tomatoes, Baby Leeks, Pommes Dauphine.jpg

Sometimes referred to as dauphine potatoes, they are crisp potato puffs made by mixing mashed potatoes with savoury choux pastry, forming the mixture into dumpling shapes, and then deep frying them at 170° to 180 °C.
Often served with duck confit. Sliced potatoes seared in goose or duck fat with garlic, then steamed until soft but still crisp.
Twice-fried slices of potato. First fried at 150 °C (300 °F), cooled, then fried again at 190 °C (375 °F), causing the slices to puff up.

A savoury dish, popular especially in Poland, where it is known as babka kartoflana, and Belarus. It is made from grated potatoes, eggs, onions, and pieces of smoked, boiled or fried bacon and (especially in Poland) sausage.
A form of bread in which potato replaces a portion of the regular wheat flour.
May refer to different preparations of potatoes
Thinly sliced potatoes that have been deep fried or baked until crunchy
Sometimes called a Spudnut, it's a doughnut, typically sweet, made with either mashed potatoes or potato starch instead of flour
Prepared with mashed potatoes, bread and additional ingredients
Shallow-fried pancakes of grated or ground potato, flour and egg, often flavored with grated onion or garlic and seasoning
A dish made from boiled potatoes that comes in many versions in different regions of the world. Though called a salad, it is generally a side dish, as it usually accompanies the main course.

A regional variant of the savoury griddle scone which is especially popular in Scotland. Many variations of the recipe exist, and they generally include liberal quantities of boiled potatoes, butter and salt.

A snack food or appetizer made with slices of half-spherical pieces of potatoes with the skin left on. They may be partially hollowed out to allow space for various toppings. The potato side is covered with toppings such as bacon, cheddar cheese, green onions, and anything else that might be found on a baked potato.
A potato-based savoury food in a waffle-like lattice shape. They are common in the UK and Ireland and are also available in some other countries.
A variation of french fries. As their name suggests, they are wedges of potatoes, often large and unpeeled, that are either baked or fried.
Pan-fried potatoes along with green and red bell peppers

May refer to two distinct potato-based dishes derived from Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine. One version is a hybrid between potato kugel and bread, containing shredded potatoes, onion, flour and leavened with yeast. Another dish, apparently unrelated but called by the same name, is essentially a very large latke meant to be cut into wedges at the table.
A common Canadian dish, originating in Quebec, made with french fries, topped with a light brown gravy-like sauce and cheese curds.
A traditional Acadian dish that in its most common form consists of a boiled potato dumpling with a pork filling; it is usually prepared with a mixture of grated and mashed potato.
Raclette is both a type of cheese and a Swiss dish based on heating the cheese and scraping off (racler) the melted part.
Patties made from boiled mashed potatoes and covered with the stew-like curry which consists of mashed and fried peas with onions, spices and tomatoes
A casserole-like dish traditionally formed by grating potatoes, then squeezing them through cheesecloth, upon which additional ingredients are added
A dumpling prepared with grated potato, salt and flour, with barley being used often
Potato fritters that are common in many areas of Germany
A traditional Māori (Polynesian) sourdough potato bread
Consists primarily of grated potatoes, and a number of additional ingredients are sometimes added
A traditional dish from the Scottish Borders. The main ingredients are potato, cabbage and onion

A fast food dish commonly consumed as street food throughout Latin America, it typically consist of thinly sliced pan-fried beef sausages and French fries, mixed together with a savory coleslaw on the side.

As the potatoes cook, the salty water forms a crust on the skin and seals the potatoes so they never taste waterlogged, as ordinary boiled potatoes often do. The potatoes have a unique texture closer to fluffy baked potatoes, only creamier.
A fast food of the Indian subcontinent with mashed potatoes and wheat as main ingredient.
A small, double-crust meat pie filled with minced mutton or other meat that may include mashed potatoes in its preparation.
In Polish: kluski śląskie. Made of boiled and then mashed potatoes (moderately cooled, but still warm), potato flour, an egg (optional) and a little bit of salt.
Composed of a slice of beef served with gravy and mashed potatoes and typically garnished with diced bacon and chopped pieces of leek
A common dish served in England consisting of sliced potatoes stacked o top of each other and baked then fried, sometimes containing root vegetables and topped with cinnemon
Potato and egg fried in olive oil (also called a tortilla)
French fries/chips chicken strips, peppers and spices
Potatoes mashed with vegetables and sausage or other stewed meats
Baked pilchards, eggs and potatoes wrapped in a pastry crust
File:Sirloin steak with garlic butter and french fries cropped.jpg
Pan-fried steak paired with deep-fried potatoes (French fries)
Fried bacon served with potatoes and a parsley sauce (med persillesovs).

A Brussels variant of the stamppot dish in the cuisine of Belgium and the Netherlands. It consists of pureed or mashed potatoes, other root vegetables and can also include cream, bacon, onion or shallot, herbs, and spices.
A stew containing potatoes with variations containing onion, leftover roast beef, corned beef, mince or sorts of meat.
A Christmas dish of puréed potatoes mixed with wheat flour.
An Indian dish: Potato chips mixed with cashew and dried grapes.
A type of potato salad made with carrots, peas, ham, various sausages, pickled fish, boiled eggs, with olive oil or mayonnaise.
Potatoes, Reblochon cheese, lardons and onions. Tartiflette is pictured on the left in the image.
Potato, young and pure cheese, salt or svanetian salt. A dish is made with boiled potatoes and young cheese, served warm.
Hash browns formed into small cylinders and deep fried
Sliced potatoes, eggplant, and red bell peppers previously fried in olive oil, served in a low-sided dish.
A dish of potatoes, cabbage, and pork. In the image Trinxat is on the right.
A kind of thick pancake of slowly cooked, thinly sliced potatoes that are then mixed with strips of tome fraiche.
A type of deep fried fritter served as a snack.
One of several dishes commended British Ministry of Food World War II to provide a nutritional diet despite food shortages and rationing, of especially meat.
Balls of breaded, mashed potato and dough shaped with minced meat filling.
